Dynamically added list items are expandables too without reinitializing

This attaches one single event handler to an expandable list, but sets
the scope to the collapsible header. This way you attach one event
handler instead of potentially hundreds and it'll make sure any new
dynamically added list item is able to be collapsed without
reinitializing the component.

Here's a quick example of what I changed: https://jsfiddle.net/nyy085de/

Note: this only changes how the expandables work, not collapsibles. I
don't have the time to have a look at the rest, but I have the feeling
that this kind of thing happens on other parts of the projects; applying
event handlers to ONLY a cached element/list of things.

Allow multiple modals

This change allows multiple modals to be opened at the same time.

How it has been done:
 - Don't use a static ID for the overlay. Use a class instead
 - Store references to the associated overlay element so each modal
   can reference its own overlay. We're generating an ID to store the reference
   so we only need to have a string as a reference instead of a whole jQuery
   object
 - Populate the z-index CSS property in JavaScript, so we can increase it for
   each new stacked modal

Also, reuse jQuery objects instead of querying the DOM each time.

Changed select change event.

It will now trigger the event instead of just calling the onchange field in the select.
Advantages of this are that alternative ways of capturing the onchange event are now allowed, e.g.

 $(document).on('change', '#mySelect', myOnchangeFunction());

 This will still fire the onchange function when passed in the select itself like e.g. <select onchange="myFunction()">

Added a callback to a select change.

Currently there is no way to attach event handlers to select elements because of the way you dynamically create your own structure to display the select. 

This callback adds this functionality through an alternative way, you can do:
$('#mySelect').material_select(myCallBackFunction);

Ofcourse, $('select').material_select(someFunction) wouldn't make sense since you would have a single function handling every select's change event, so you should just use this on a single element.
